<TITLE> England press for victory with four wickets </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BIRMINGHAM, England, Aug 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South Africa, chasing 281 for victory, lost four wickets for 28 runs to slump to 111 for four at tea on the fourth day of the third test against England at Edgbaston on Saturday. Captain Graeme Smith was undefeated on 55 and AB de Villiers nine not out after Neil McKenzie (22), Hashim Amla (6), Jacques Kallis (5) and Ashwell Prince (2) had been removed. Smith reached his half-century in 86 balls and a lot of pressure is resting on his shoulders as South Africa, already 1-0 up, look to secure victory in the four-match series. The visitors were 65 for no loss when McKenzie was trapped lbw by Andrew Flintoff. Amla then fell lbw to Monty Panesar before Kallis was also trapped leg before after losing sight of a high full toss from Flintoff. Kallis left the field in angry mood after remonstrating with umpire Steve Davis. Prince then edged James Anderson to wicketkeeper Tim Ambrose. Earlier, England were bowled out in their second innings for 363 with Paul Collingwood scoring 135
